<font color="#FF0000">SPECIAL TRAINING</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep 27 14:17:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook and others,<br><br>
What Cook has said about his training and it's effects on not only keeping him alive, but also giving him defense mechanisms against PTSD, ring true to me too.  Like Cook, my training was intensive, and included aircrew survival school, with it's POW camp and escape and invasion course at Fairchild AFB in Washington; US Army Mountain Ranger School in Georgia; Panama Jungle Survival School; and PJSS (Philippine Jungle Survival School).  Pararescue was and is one of the Special Forces, but our charge wasn't to kill, but to save aircrew lives.  <br><br>
I cannot say that the intensity of our Air Force training was as great as what Cook experienced.  There is no way that I would make a parachute jump with defective equipment--we always checked that stuff out ourselves.  We were responsible for our own gear, and did the parachute packing ourselves.  <br><br>
Having defective LPUs (Underarm Life Preservers, for those who haven't heard the term before; they were folded into a pouch which attached via a harness under each arm) and one-man life rafts which did not work seems pretty malicious to me, but also in keeping with what I've heard about the Marines.  <br><br>
I have always felt that we were much, much better trained to handle almost any circumstance than were the &quot;common grunts.&quot;  I've advised people that if they were going into a dangerous situation such as Vietnam, to get into one of the Special Forces because they would actually have a better chance of surviving!  Special Forces operate much differently than the regular forces, and usually didn't fair too badly.  But when bad things happened, it could be really bad too.  So you make your decisions, and take your chances.  Mine worked out okay.<br><br>
The Special Forces were:  US Army Green Berets, US Navy SEAL Teams, US Air Force Pararescue and (later) Combat Controller, US Marines Force Recon.  <br><br>
Cook, it sounds from what you've written that you were in one of the Force Recon units.  Any comments (sometimes this is stuff that still isn't mentioned).  <br>

